'''Shimoikeyama Kofun''' (下池山古墳) is a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] located in [[:en:Tenri, Nara|Tenri, Nara Prefecture]], Narogaji Town. It is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/keyhole-shaped tumulus|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=}} and part of the {{ill|Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|ja|大和古墳群|1=Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=}} (Kayao subgroup). Designated as a national [[:en:Historic site|Historic site of Japan]]} (as part of the "Ōyamato Kofun Cluster"), its excavated burial goods are registered as Nara Prefecture Designated Historic site.

== Overview ==
The mound is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/keyhole-shaped tumulus|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=}} with a length of approximately 120 meters. Excavations conducted by the {{ill|Kashihara Archaeological Institute|ja|奈良県立橿原考古学研究所附属博物館|10=ja|11=奈良県立橿原考古学研究所附属博物館|comment=trying to get the bot to work with these using this|ja|奈良県立橿原考古学研究所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute|qq=}} between [[:en:1995|1995]] and [[:en:1996|1996]] revealed a {{ill|pit-style stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pit-style stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}. This chamber, measuring 6.8 meters in length and constructed using numerous stone slabs, contained a wooden coffin and iron burial goods. Additionally, a smaller chamber was discovered on the northwest side of the main chamber, where a large [[:en:Flower mirror|mirrored bronze with flower patterns]] was unearthed. Based on accompanying burial goods, the tumulus is estimated to have been constructed in the early [[:en:4th century|4th century]].

<gallery>
File:下池山古墳出土 割竹形木棺-2.JPG|Split bamboo-style wooden coffin (Nara Prefecture Designated Tangible Cultural Property)<br/>{{small|Displayed at the [[:en:The Museum, Archaeological Institute of Kashihara, Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute Museum]].}}
File:下池山古墳出土 割竹形木棺.JPG|Split bamboo-style wooden coffin (from another angle)
File:下池山古墳 Excavated Artifacts.JPG|excavations (Nara Prefecture Designated Tangible Cultural Property)<br/>{{small|Displayed at the [[:en:The Museum, Archaeological Institute of Kashihara, Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute Museum]].}}
</gallery>

== Historic site ==
=== National Historic site ===
* '''Shimoikeyama Kofun''' (part of the "Ōyamato Kofun Cluster") – On October 6, 2014, the {{ill|Nomugi Kofun|ja|ノムギ古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nomugi Kofun|qq=}}, {{ill|Nakayama Ōtsuka Kofun|lt=Nakayama Ōtsuka Kofun|lt=Nakayama Otsuka Kofun|ja|中山大塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakayama Otsuka Kofun|qq=}}, and Shimoikeyama Kofun were collectively Historic site as the "Ōyamato Kofun Cluster."

=== Nara Prefecture Designated Historic site ===
* '''burial goods from Shimoikeyama Kofun''' (archaeological materials) – Preserved and displayed at the [[:en:The Museum, Archaeological Institute of Kashihara, Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute Museum]]. Designated on March 31, 2006.

== Related Facilities ==
* [[:en:The Museum, Archaeological Institute of Kashihara, Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute Museum]] (Kashihara City, Unebi Town) – Houses and displays burial goods from Shimoikeyama Kofun.

